# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: zigbee-3
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] The 6LoWPAN group defined encapsulation, header compression, neighbor discovery and other mechanisms that allow IPv6 to operate over IEEE 802.15.4 based networks.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Although IPv4 and IPv6 protocols do not generally care about the physical and MAC layers they operate over, the low-power devices and small packet size defined by IEEE 802.15.4 make it desirable to adapt to these layers.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] The base specification developed by the 6LoWPAN IETF group is RFC 4944 (updated by RFC 6282 with header compression, RFC 6775 with neighbor discovery optimization, RFC 8931 with selective fragment recovery and with smaller changes in RFC 8025 and RFC 8066).
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] The problem statement document is RFC 4919.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] IPv6 over Bluetooth Low Energy using 6LoWPAN techniques is described in RFC 7668.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] The targets for IPv6 networking for low-power radio communication are devices that need wireless connectivity to many other devices at lower data rates for devices with very limited power consumption.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] The header compression mechanisms in RFC 6282 are used to allow IPv6 packets to travel over such networks.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] IPv6 is also in use on the smart grid enabling smart meters and other devices to build a micro mesh network before sending the data back to the billing system using the IPv6 backbone.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Some of these networks run over IEEE 802.15.4 radios, and therefore use the header compression and fragmentation as specified by RFC6282.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Thread is a standard from a group of more than fifty companies for a protocol running over 6LoWPAN to enable home automation.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] The specification is available at no cost as of 24 June 2022, but paid membership is required to implement the protocol.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Version 1.0 of the specification was published on 2015-10-29.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] The protocol most directly competes with Z-Wave and Zigbee IP.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] In IoT device communications using the Matter standard, Thread is one of two possible wireless transport layers.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] As with all link-layer mappings of IP, RFC4944 provides a number of functions.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Beyond the usual differences between L2 and L3 networks, mapping from the IPv6 network to the IEEE 802.15.4 network poses additional design challenges (see RFC 4919 for an overview).
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] IPv6 requires the link maximum transmission unit (MTU) to be at least 1280 octets.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] In contrast, IEEE 802.15.4's standard frame size is 127 octets.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] A maximum frame overhead of 25 octets and an optional but highly recommended security feature at the link layer poses an additional overhead of up to 21 octets are for AES-CCM-128.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] This leaves only 81 octets for the upper layers.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Since this is so much less than 1280, 6LoWPAN defines a fragmentation and reassembly layer.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Further, the standard IPv6 Header is 40 octets long, so header compression is defined as well.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] IPv6 nodes are assigned 128 bit IP addresses in a hierarchical manner, through an arbitrary length network prefix.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] IEEE 802.15.4 devices may use either of IEEE 64 bit extended addresses or, after an association event, 16 bit addresses that are unique within a PAN.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] There is also a PAN-ID for a group of physically collocated IEEE 802.15.4 devices.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] IEEE 802.15.4 devices are intentionally constrained in form factor to reduce costs (allowing for large-scale network of many devices), reduce power consumption (allowing battery powered devices) and allow flexibility of installation (e.g. small devices for body-worn networks).
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] On the other hand, wired nodes in the IP domain are not constrained in this way; they can be larger and make use of mains power supplies.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] IPv6 nodes are geared towards attaining high speeds.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Algorithms and protocols implemented at the higher layers such as TCP kernel of the TCP/IP are optimized to handle typical network problems such as congestion.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] In IEEE 802.15.4-compliant devices, energy conservation and code-size optimization remain at the top of the agenda.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] An adaptation mechanism to allow interoperability between IPv6 domain and the IEEE 802.15.4 can best be viewed as a layer problem.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Identifying the functionality of this layer and defining newer packet formats, if needed, is an enticing research area.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] RFC 4944 proposes an adaptation layer to allow the transmission of IPv6 datagrams over IEEE 802.15.4 networks.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] The management of addresses for devices that communicate across the two dissimilar domains of IPv6 and IEEE 802.15.4 is cumbersome, if not exhaustingly complex.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Several routing protocols have been proposed by the 6LoWPAN community such as LOAD, DYMO-LOW, HI-LOW.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] However, only two routing protocols are currently legitimate for large-scale deployments: LOADng standardized by the ITU under the recommendation ITU-T G.9903 and RPL standardized by the IETF ROLL working group.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] The 6LoWPAN routing scheme can be carried out in two different ways: *mesh-under* and *route-over*.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Initially, several routing protocols were developed by the 6LoWPAN community, such as LOAD, DYMO-LOW, HI-LOW .
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Since IP-enabled devices may require the formation of ad hoc networks, the current state of neighboring devices and the services hosted by such devices will need to be known.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] IPv6 neighbour discovery extensions is an internet draft proposed as a contribution in this area.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] IEEE 802.15.4 nodes can operate in either secure mode or non-secure mode.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] There RFC 4944 defines the IPv6 header compression mechanism for LowPAN: LOWPAN_HC1.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] It also includes compression of the UDP header over 4 bytes, but does not allow compression of the *Checksum*.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Additionally, it restricts the range of UDP ports from 61616 to 61631 in order to compress this value to 4 bits.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] This IPv6 header compression can only be applied to local link addresses.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] To overcome this problem, an IETF LOWPAN_HC1g draft was published.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] LOWPAN_HC1g applies to global addresses for IP multi-hop communications.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] These two compression mechanisms (LOWPAN_HC1 and LOWPAN_HC1g) are complementary.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] It is therefore necessary to implement both.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Today the proposal of the 6LoWPAN group is to use LOWPAN_IPHC.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] IPHC bytes result from compression of the IPv6 header.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] They mainly integrate information from quality of service (DSCP and ECN), next headers, number of hops and compressed source/destination addresses.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] The example below shows the increase in payload compared to the original problem (see 1re figure).
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] This payload is in the best case 70 to 75 bytes.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Indeed, if we add the fragmentation information as indicated in the paragraph above, it will decrease to 65-70 bytes for this scenario.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Technological developments in the 1990s (miniaturization of electronics, deployment of new wireless networks and embedded systems) enabled the emergence of new applications for sensor and actuator networks.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] With the advent of wireless technologies, the first solutions used were completely proprietary (for example Z-Wave or EnOcean).
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] With the standard IEEE 802.15.4 (radio use of wireless sensors) new proprietary standards have appeared (for example, ZigBee, WirelessHART **(in)**, etc.).
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] When first thinking about wireless sensor networking, 6LoWPAN was born from a simple idea: why reinvent a protocol when we already have IP?
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Geoff Mulligan proposes the use of IP on 802.15.4 for sensor type equipment.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] , "robust header compression") of IETF were interested.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] A first implementation of 6LoWPAN on TinyOS released on the implementation of "Arch Rock Company: Primer Pack/IP".
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] A first implementation of 6LoWPAN on TinyOS is available on the implementation of "Sensinode Company: NanoStack v0.9.4".
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] The 6LoWPAN group publishes the RFC 4919 to ensure the interoperability of the network layer.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] There RFC 4944 sees the light of day, based on the RFC4919.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] This should allow direct connectivity to the Internet of LoWPAN equipment via IPv6 and replace them communication protocols owners like ZigBee,, which was developed after the end of the Smart Dust project.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] The IETF launches the ROLL Working Group.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] , "IP for Smart Objects"), chaired by Geoff Mulligan, is created to promote the use of IP in smart objects.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Smart objects are small type objects switch, detector more commonly called sensors.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] To develop smart grids, President Obama announces an investment of $3.4 billion.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Study demonstrates significant economic prospects in IoT.
[src:zigbee-3/6lowpan] Cisco buys the company Arch Rock (one of the leaders in BAC applications for WSN), which strengthens the strategic alliance previously signed between Cisco and Itron (metering specialist smart grid),.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] The phrase **smart home** refers to home automation devices that have internet access.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Home automation, a broader category, includes *any* device that can be monitored or controlled via wireless radio signals, not just those having internet access.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] When connected with the Internet, home sensors and activation devices are an important constituent of the Internet of Things ("IoT").
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] A home automation system typically connects controlled devices to a central smart home hub (sometimes called a "gateway").
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] The user interface for control of the system uses either wall-mounted terminals, tablet or desktop computers, a mobile phone application, or a Web interface that may also be accessible off-site through the Internet.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Early home automation began with labor-saving machines.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Self-contained electric or gas powered home appliances became viable in the 1900s with the introduction of electric power distribution and led to the introduction of washing machines (1904), water heaters (1889), refrigerators (1913), sewing machines, dishwashers, and clothes dryers.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] In 1975, the first general purpose home automation network technology, X10, was developed.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] It is a communication protocol for electronic devices.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] It primarily uses electric power transmission wiring for signalling and control, where the signals involve brief radio frequency bursts of digital data, and remains the most widely available.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] By 2012, in the United States, according to ABI Research, 1.5 million home automation systems were installed.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Per research firm Statista more than 45 million smart home devices will be installed in U.S. homes by the end of the year 2018.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] From 2018 to 2023, the number of U.S. homes equipped with smart devices grew at 10.2% per year to reach 63.43 million by 2023.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] The word "*domotics*" is a contraction of the Latin word for a home (*domus*) and the word *robotics*.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] The word "smart" in "smart home" refers to the system being aware of the state of its devices, which is done through the information and communication technologies (ICT) protocol and the Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] In 2011, Microsoft Research found that home automation could involve a high cost of ownership, inflexibility of interconnected devices, and poor manageability.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] When designing and creating a home automation system, engineers take into account several factors including scalability, how well the devices can be monitored and controlled, ease of installation and use for the consumer, affordability, speed, security, and ability to diagnose issues.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Findings from iControl showed that consumers prioritize ease-of-use over technical innovation, and although consumers recognize that new connected devices have an unparalleled cool factor, they are not quite ready to use them in their own homes yet.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Historically, systems have been sold as complete systems where the consumer relies on one vendor for the entire system including the hardware, the communications protocol, the central hub, and the user interface.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] However, there are now open hardware and open source software systems which can be used instead of or with proprietary hardware.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Many of these systems interface with consumer electronics such as the Arduino or Raspberry Pi, which are easily accessible online and in most electronics stores.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] In addition, home automation devices are increasingly interfaced with mobile phones through Bluetooth, allowing for increased affordability and customizability for the user.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Customers may hesitate to bet their IoT future on proprietary software or hardware devices that use proprietary protocols that may fade or become difficult to customize and interconnect.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] The nature of home automation devices can also be a problem for security, data security and data privacy, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] One set of researchers say that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active devices vulnerable.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Concerns have been raised by tenants renting from landlords who decide to upgrade units with smart home technology.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] These concerns include weak wireless connections that render the door or appliance unusable or impractical; the security of door passcodes kept by the landlord; and the potential invasion of privacy that comes with connecting smart home technologies to home networks.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Researchers have also conducted user studies to determine what the barriers are for consumers when integrating home automation devices or systems into their daily lifestyle.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] One of the main takeaways was regarding ease of use, as consumers tend to steer towards "plug and play" solutions over more complicated setups.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] One study found that there were large gaps in the mental-models generated by users regarding how the devices actually work.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Specifically, the findings showed that there was a lot of misunderstanding related to where the data collected by smart devices was stored and how it was used.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] For example, in a smart light setup, one participant thought that her iPad communicated directly with the light, telling it to either turn-off or on.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] In reality, the iPad sends a signal to the cloud system that the company uses (in this case, the Hue Bridge) which then signals directly to the device.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Overall, this field is still evolving and the nature of each device is constantly changing.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] While technologists work to create more secure, streamlined, and standardized security protocols, consumers also need to learn more about how these devices work and what the implications of putting them in their homes can be.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] The growth of this field is currently limited not only by technology but also by a user's ability to trust a device and integrate it successfully into his/her daily life.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Utilizing home automation could lead to more efficient and intelligent energy-saving techniques.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] To do this, researchers propose using data from sensors regarding consumer activity within the home to anticipate consumer needs and balance that with energy consumption.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Furthermore, home automation has a large potential regarding family safety and security.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] According to a 2015 survey done by iControl, the primary drivers of the demand for smart and connected devices are first "personal and family security", and second "excitement about energy savings".
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Home automation includes a variety of smart security systems and surveillance setups.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] This allows consumers to monitor their homes while away, and to give trusted family members access to that information in case anything bad happens.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] While there are many competing vendors, there are increasing efforts towards open source systems.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] However, there are issues with the current state of home automation including a lack of standardized security measures and deprecation of older devices without backwards compatibility.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] Home automation has high potential for sharing data between family members or trusted individuals for personal security purposes and could lead to energy saving measures with a positive environmental impact in the future.
[src:zigbee-3/home-automation] The home automation market was worth US$64 billion in 2022 and is projected to grow to over $163 billion in 2028.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE standard 802.15.4 is intended to offer the fundamental lower network layers of a type of wireless personal area network (WPAN), which focuses on low-cost, low-speed ubiquitous communication between devices.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] It can be contrasted with other approaches, such as Wi-Fi, which offers more bandwidth and requires more power.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] The emphasis is on very low-cost communication of nearby devices with little to no underlying infrastructure, intending to exploit this to lower power consumption even more.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] The basic framework conceives a 10-meter communications range with line of sight at a transfer rate of 250 kbit/s.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Bandwidth tradeoffs are possible to favor more radically embedded devices with even lower power requirements for increased battery operating time, through the definition of not one, but several physical layers.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Lower transfer rates of 20 and 40 kbit/s were initially defined, with the 100 kbit/s rate being added in the current revision.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Even lower rates can be used, which results in lower power consumption.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] As already mentioned, the main goal of IEEE 802.15.4 regarding WPANs is the emphasis on achieving low manufacturing and operating costs through the use of relatively simple transceivers, while enabling application flexibility and adaptability.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Integrated support for secure communications.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Power management functions to adjust compromises of link speed and quality and energy detection.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Support for time- and data-rate–sensitive applications through the ability to operate with either CSMA/CA or TDMA access modes.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] The TDMA mode of operation is supported via the GTS feature of the standard.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE 802.15.4-conformant devices may use one of three possible frequency bands for operation (868/915/2450 MHz).
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Devices are designed to interact with each other over a conceptually simple wireless network.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] The definition of the network layers is based on the OSI model; although only the lower layers are defined in the standard, interaction with upper layers is intended, possibly using an IEEE 802.2 logical link control sublayer accessing the MAC through a convergence sublayer.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Implementations may rely on external devices or be purely embedded, self-functioning devices.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] The *physical layer* (PHY) provides the data transmission service.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] It also, provides an interface to the *physical layer management entity*, which offers access to every physical layer management function and maintains a database of information on related personal area networks.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Thus, the PHY manages the physical radio transceiver, performs channel selection along with energy and signal management functions.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] An optional alternative 868/915 MHz layer is defined using a combination of binary keying and amplitude-shift keying (thus based on parallel, not sequential, spread spectrum; PSSS).
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Dynamic switching between supported 868/915 MHz PHYs is possible.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Beyond these three bands, the IEEE 802.15.4c study group considered the newly opened 314–316 MHz, 430–434 MHz, and 779–787 MHz bands in China, while the IEEE 802.15 Task Group 4d defined an amendment to to support the new 950–956 MHz band in Japan.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] The first standard amendments by these groups were released in April 2009.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE 802.15.4e was chartered to define a MAC amendment to the existing standard 802.15.4-2006 which adopts a channel hopping strategy to improve support for the industrial market.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Channel hopping increases robustness against external interference and persistent multi-path fading.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] On February 6, 2012, the IEEE Standards Association Board approved IEEE 802.15.4e which concluded all Task Group 4e efforts.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] The medium access control (MAC) enables the transmission of MAC frames through the use of the physical channel.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Besides the data service, it offers a management interface and itself manages access to the physical channel and network beaconing.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] It also controls frame validation, guarantees time slots and handles node associations.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Finally, it offers hook points for secure services.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Note that the IEEE 802.15 standard does *not* use 802.1d or IEEE standard 802.15.4q-2016; i.e., it does not exchange standard Ethernet frames.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] The physical frame-format is specified in IEEE standard 802.15.4-2011 in section 5.2.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] It is tailored to the fact that most IEEE 802.15.4 PHYs only support frames of up to 127 bytes (adaptation layer protocols such as the IETF's 6LoWPAN provide fragmentation schemes to support larger network layer packets).
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] No higher-level layers or interoperability sublayers are defined in the standard.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Other specifications, such as Zigbee, SNAP, and 6LoWPAN/Thread, build on this standard.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] RIOT, OpenWSN, TinyOS, Unison RTOS, DSPnano RTOS, nanoQplus, Contiki and Zephyr operating systems also use some components of IEEE standard 802.15.4-2020 hardware and software.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] The standard defines two types of network node.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] The first one is the **full-function device** (FFD).
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] It can serve as the coordinator of a personal area network just as it may function as a common node.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] It implements a general model of communication which allows it to talk to any other device: it may also relay messages, in which case it is dubbed a coordinator (PAN coordinator when it is in charge of the whole network).
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] On the other hand, there are **reduced-function devices** (RFD).
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] These are meant to be extremely simple devices with very modest resource and communication requirements; due to this, they can only communicate with FFDs and can never act as coordinators.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Networks can be built as either peer-to-peer or star networks.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] However, every network needs at least one FFD to work as the coordinator of the network.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Networks are thus formed by groups of devices separated by suitable distances.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Each device has a unique 64-bit identifier, and if some conditions are met, short 16-bit identifiers can be used within a restricted environment.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Namely, within each PAN domain, communications will probably use short identifiers.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] A more structured **star** pattern is also supported, where the coordinator of the network will necessarily be the central node.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Such a network can originate when an FFD decides to create its own PAN and declare itself its coordinator, after choosing a unique PAN identifier.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] After that, other devices can join the network, which is fully independent from all other star networks.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Frames are the basic unit of data transport, of which there are four fundamental types (data, acknowledgment, beacon and MAC command frames), which provide a reasonable tradeoff between simplicity and robustness.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Additionally, a superframe structure, defined by the coordinator, may be used, in which case two beacons act as its limits and provide synchronization to other devices as well as configuration information.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] A superframe consists of sixteen equal-length slots, which can be further divided into an active part and an inactive part, during which the coordinator may enter power saving mode, not needing to control its network.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Within superframes contention occurs between their limits, and is resolved by CSMA/CA.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Every transmission must end before the arrival of the second beacon.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] As mentioned before, applications with well-defined bandwidth needs can use up to seven domains of one or more contentionless guaranteed time slots, trailing at the end of the superframe.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] The first part of the superframe must be sufficient to give service to the network structure and its devices.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Superframes are typically utilized within the context of low-latency devices, whose associations must be kept even if inactive for long periods of time.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Data transfers to the coordinator require a beacon synchronization phase, if applicable, followed by CSMA/CA transmission (by means of slots if superframes are in use); acknowledgment is optional.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Data transfers from the coordinator usually follow device requests: if beacons are in use, these are used to signal requests; the coordinator acknowledges the request and then sends the data in packets which are acknowledged by the device.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] The same is done when superframes are not in use, only in this case there are no beacons to keep track of pending messages.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Point-to-point networks may either use unslotted CSMA/CA or synchronization mechanisms; in this case, communication between any two devices is possible, whereas in "structured" modes one of the devices must be the network coordinator.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] In general, all implemented procedures follow a typical request-confirm/indication-response classification.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] The physical medium is accessed through a CSMA/CA access method.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Networks which are not using beaconing mechanisms utilize an unslotted variation which is based on the listening of the medium, leveraged by a random exponential backoff algorithm; acknowledgments do not adhere to this discipline.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Common data transmission utilizes unallocated slots when beaconing is in use; again, confirmations do not follow the same process.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Confirmation messages may be optional under certain circumstances, in which case a success assumption is made.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Whatever the case, if a device is unable to process a frame at a given time, it simply does not confirm its reception: timeout-based retransmission can be performed a number of times, following after that a decision of whether to abort or keep trying.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Because the predicted environment of these devices demands maximization of battery life, the protocols tend to favor the methods which lead to it, implementing periodic checks for pending messages, the frequency of which depends on application needs.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Regarding secure communications, the MAC sublayer offers facilities which can be harnessed by upper layers to achieve the desired level of security.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Higher-layer processes may specify keys to perform symmetric cryptography to protect the payload and restrict it to a group of devices or just a point-to-point link; these groups of devices can be specified in access control lists.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] Furthermore, MAC computes *freshness checks* between successive receptions to ensure that presumably old frames, or data which is no longer considered valid, does not transcend to higher layers.
[src:zigbee-3/ieee-802-15-4] In addition to this secure mode, there is another, insecure MAC mode, which allows access control lists merely as a means to decide on the acceptance of frames according to their (presumed) source.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] A **mesh network** is a network topology in which the infrastructure nodes (i.e., bridges, switches, and other infrastructure devices) connect directly, dynamically and non-hierarchically to as many other nodes as possible and cooperate with one another to efficiently route data to and from hosts.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] This lack of dependency on one node allows for every node to participate in the relay of information.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] Mesh networks dynamically self-organize and self-configure, which can reduce installation overhead.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] The ability to self-configure enables dynamic distribution of workloads, particularly in the event that a few nodes should fail.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] This, in turn, contributes to fault-tolerance and reduced maintenance costs.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] Mesh topology may be contrasted with conventional star/tree network topologies in which the bridges/switches are directly linked to only a small subset of other bridges/switches, and the links between these infrastructure neighbours are hierarchical.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] While star-and-tree topologies are very well established, highly standardized and vendor-neutral, vendors of mesh network devices have not yet all agreed on common standards, and interoperability between devices from different vendors is not yet assured.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] Mesh networks can relay messages using either a *flooding* or a *routing* technique, which makes them different from non-mesh networks.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] A routed message is propagated along a path by *hopping* from node to node until it reaches its destination.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] To ensure that all its paths are available, the network must allow for continuous connections and must reconfigure itself around broken paths, using *self-healing* algorithms such as Shortest Path Bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links).
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] Self-healing allows a routing-based network to operate when a node breaks down or when a connection becomes unreliable.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] The network is typically quite reliable, as there is often more than one path between a source and a destination in the network.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] Although mostly used in wireless situations, this concept can also apply to wired networks and to software interaction.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] A mesh network whose nodes are all connected to each other is a fully connected network.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] Fully connected wired networks are more secure and reliable: problems in a cable affect only the two nodes attached to it.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] In such networks, however, the number of cables, and therefore the cost, goes up rapidly as the number of nodes increases.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] Shortest path bridging and TRILL each allow Ethernet switches to be connected in a mesh topology and allow for all paths to be active.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] IP routing supports multiple paths from source to destination.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] A wireless mesh network (WMN) is a network made up of radio nodes organized in a mesh topology.
[src:zigbee-3/mesh-networking] It can also be a form of wireless ad hoc network.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] These are similar to wireless ad hoc networks in the sense that they rely on wireless connectivity and spontaneous formation of networks so that sensor data can be transported wirelessly.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs monitor physical conditions, such as temperature, sound, and pressure.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Modern networks are bi-directional, both collecting data and enabling control of sensor activity.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The development of these networks was motivated by military applications such as battlefield surveillance.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Such networks are used in industrial and consumer applications, such as industrial process monitoring and control and machine health monitoring and agriculture.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] A WSN is built of "nodes" – from a few to hundreds or thousands, where each node is connected to other sensors.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Each such node typically has several parts: a radio transceiver with an internal antenna or connection to an external antenna, a microcontroller, an electronic circuit for interfacing with the sensors and an energy source, usually a battery or an embedded form of energy harvesting.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] A sensor node might vary in size from a shoebox to (theoretically) a grain of dust, although microscopic dimensions have yet to be realized.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor node cost is similarly variable, ranging from a few to hundreds of dollars, depending on node sophistication.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Size and cost constraints constrain resources such as energy, memory, computational speed and communications bandwidth.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The topology of a WSN can vary from a simple star network to an advanced multi-hop wireless mesh network.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Propagation can employ routing or flooding.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] As of 2010, wireless sensor networks had deployed approximately 120 million remote units worldwide.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Area monitoring is a common application of WSNs.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] In area monitoring, the WSN is deployed over a region where some phenomenon is to be monitored.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] A military example is the use of sensors to detect enemy intrusion; a civilian example is the geo-fencing of gas or oil pipelines.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] There are several types of sensor networks for medical applications: implanted, wearable, and environment-embedded.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Implantable medical devices are those that are inserted inside the human body.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Wearable devices are used on the body surface of a human or just at close proximity of the user.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Environment-embedded systems employ sensors contained in the environment.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Possible applications include body position measurement, location of persons, overall monitoring of ill patients in hospitals and at home.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Devices embedded in the environment track the physical state of a person for continuous health diagnosis, using as input the data from a network of depth cameras, a sensing floor, or other similar devices.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Body-area networks can collect information about an individual's health, fitness, and energy expenditure.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] In health care applications the privacy and authenticity of user data has prime importance.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Especially due to the integration of sensor networks, with IoT, the user authentication becomes more challenging; however, a solution is presented in recent work.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been used to monitor various species and habitats, beginning with the Great Duck Island Deployment, including marmots, cane toads in Australia and zebras in Kenya.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] There are many applications in monitoring environmental parameters, examples of which are given below.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] They share the extra challenges of harsh environments and reduced power supply.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Experiments have shown that personal exposure to air pollution in cities can vary a lot.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, it is of interest to have higher temporal and spatial resolution of pollutants and particulates.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] For research purposes, wireless sensor networks have been deployed to monitor the concentration of dangerous gases for citizens (e.g., in London).
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] However, sensors for gases and particulate matter suffer from high unit-to-unit variability, cross-sensitivities, and (concept) drift.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Moreover, the quality of data is currently insufficient for trustworthy decision-making, as field calibration leads to unreliable measurement results, and frequent recalibration might be required.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] A possible solution could be blind calibration or the usage of mobile references.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] A network of Sensor Nodes can be installed in a forest to detect when a fire has started.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The nodes can be equipped with sensors to measure temperature, humidity and gases which are produced by fire in the trees or vegetation.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The early detection is crucial for a successful action of the firefighters; thanks to Wireless Sensor Networks, the fire brigade will be able to know when a fire is started and how it is spreading.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] A landslide detection system makes use of a wireless sensor network to detect the slight movements of soil and changes in various parameters that may occur before or during a landslide.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Through the data gathered it may be possible to know the impending occurrence of landslides long before it actually happens.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Water quality monitoring involves analyzing water properties in dams, rivers, lakes and oceans, as well as underground water reserves.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The use of many wireless distributed sensors enables the creation of a more accurate map of the water status, and allows the permanent deployment of monitoring stations in locations of difficult access, without the need of manual data retrieval.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks can be effective in preventing adverse consequences of natural disasters, like floods.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless nodes have been deployed successfully in rivers, where changes in water levels must be monitored in real time.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been developed for machinery condition-based maintenance (CBM) as they offer significant cost savings and enable new functionality.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensors can be placed in locations difficult or impossible to reach with a wired system, such as rotating machinery and untethered vehicles.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks also are used for the collection of data for monitoring of environmental information.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] This can be as simple as monitoring the temperature in a fridge or the level of water in overflow tanks in nuclear power plants.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The statistical information can then be used to show how systems have been working.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The advantage of WSNs over conventional loggers is the "live" data feed that is possible.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Monitoring the quality and level of water includes many activities such as checking the quality of underground or surface water and ensuring a country's water infrastructure for the benefit of both human and animal.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] It may be used to protect the wastage of water.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] WSN can be used to monitor the condition of civil infrastructure and related geo-physical processes close to real time, and over long periods through data logging, using appropriately interfaced sensors.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are used to monitor wine production, both in the field and the cellar.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The Wide Area Tracking System (WATS) is a prototype network for detecting a ground-based nuclear device such as a nuclear "briefcase bomb".
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] WATS is being developed at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL).
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would be made up of wireless gamma and neutron sensors connected through a communications network.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Data picked up by the sensors undergoes "data fusion", which converts the information into easily interpreted forms; this data fusion is the most important aspect of the system.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The data fusion process occurs *within* the sensor network rather than at a centralized computer and is performed by a specially developed algorithm based on Bayesian statistics.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would not use a centralized computer for analysis because researchers found that factors such as latency and available bandwidth tended to create significant bottlenecks.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Data processed in the field by the network itself (by transferring small amounts of data between neighboring sensors) is faster and makes the network more scalable.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] An important factor in WATS development is *ease of deployment*, since more sensors both improves the detection rate and reduces false alarms.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] WATS sensors could be deployed in permanent positions or mounted in vehicles for mobile protection of specific locations.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] One barrier to the implementation of WATS is the size, weight, energy requirements and cost of currently available wireless sensors.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The development of improved sensors is a major component of current research at the Nonproliferation, Arms Control, and International Security (NAI) Directorate at LLNL.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] House of Representatives' Military Research and Development Subcommittee on October 1, 1997, during a hearing on nuclear terrorism and countermeasures.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] On August 4, 1998, in a subsequent meeting of that subcommittee, Chairman Curt Weldon stated that research funding for WATS had been cut by the Clinton administration to a subsistence level and that the program had been poorly re-organized.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Studies show that using sensors for incident monitoring improve the response of firefighters and police to an unexpected situation.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] For an early detection of incidents we can use acoustic sensors to detect a spike in the noise of the city because of a possible accident, or use termic sensors to detect a possible fire.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Using low-power electronics, WSN:s can be cost-efficiently applied also in supply chains in various industries.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Cross-layer is becoming an important studying area for wireless communications.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The traditional layered approach does not have the ability to adapt to the environmental change.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Because of the interference between the different users, access conflicts, fading, and the change of environment in the wireless sensor networks, traditional layered approach for wired networks is not applicable to wireless networks.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] So the cross-layer can be used to make the optimal modulation to improve the transmission performance, such as data rate, energy efficiency, quality of service (QoS), etc.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor nodes can be imagined as small computers which are extremely basic in terms of their interfaces and their components.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] They usually consist of a *processing unit* with limited computational power and limited memory, *sensors* or MEMS (including specific conditioning circuitry), a *communication device* (usually radio transceivers or alternatively optical), and a power source usually in the form of a battery.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Other possible inclusions are energy harvesting modules, secondary ASICs, and possibly secondary communication interface (e.g.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The base stations are one or more components of the WSN with much more computational, energy and communication resources.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] They act as a gateway between sensor nodes and the end user as they typically forward data from the WSN on to a server.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Other special components in routing based networks are routers, designed to compute, calculate and distribute the routing tables.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] One major challenge in a WSN is to produce *low cost* and *tiny* sensor nodes.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] There are an increasing number of small companies producing WSN hardware and the commercial situation can be compared to home computing in the 1970s.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Many of the nodes are still in the research and development stage, particularly their software.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Also inherent to sensor network adoption is the use of very low power methods for radio communication and data acquisition.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] In many applications, a WSN communicates with a local area network or wide area network through a gateway.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The Gateway acts as a bridge between the WSN and the other network.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] This enables data to be stored and processed by devices with more resources, for example, in a remotely located server.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] A wireless wide area network used primarily for low-power devices is known as a Low-Power Wide-Area Network (LPWAN).
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] There are several wireless standards and solutions for sensor node connectivity.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Thread and Zigbee can connect sensors operating at 2.4 GHz with a data rate of 250 kbit/s.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Many use a lower frequency to increase radio range (typically 1 km), for example Z-wave operates at 915 MHz (in North America) and in the EU 868 MHz has been widely used but these have a lower data rate (typically 50 kbit/s).
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The IEEE 802.15.4 working group provides a standard for low power device connectivity and commonly sensors and smart meters use one of these standards for connectivity.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] With the emergence of Internet of Things, many other proposals have been made to provide sensor connectivity.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] LoRa is a form of LPWAN which provides long range low power wireless connectivity for devices, which has been used in smart meters and other long range sensor applications.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] NarrowBand IOT and LTE-M can connect up to millions of sensors and devices using cellular technology.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Energy is the scarcest resource of WSN nodes, and it determines the lifetime of WSNs.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs may be deployed in large numbers in various environments, including remote and hostile regions, where ad hoc communications are a key component.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Lifetime maximization: Energy/Power Consumption of the sensing device should be minimized and sensor nodes should be energy efficient since their limited energy resource determines their lifetime.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] To conserve power, wireless sensor nodes normally power off both the radio transmitter and the radio receiver when not in use.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are composed of low-energy, small-size, and low-range unattended sensor nodes.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Recently, it has been observed that by periodically turning on and off the sensing and communication capabilities of sensor nodes, we can significantly reduce the active time and thus prolong network lifetime.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] However, this duty cycling may result in high network latency, routing overhead, and neighbor discovery delays due to asynchronous sleep and wake-up scheduling.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] These limitations call for a countermeasure for duty-cycled wireless sensor networks which should minimize routing information, routing traffic load, and energy consumption.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers from Sungkyunkwan University have proposed a lightweight non-increasing delivery-latency interval routing referred as LNDIR.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] This scheme can discover minimum latency routes at each non-increasing delivery-latency interval instead of each time slot.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Simulation experiments demonstrated the validity of this novel approach in minimizing routing information stored at each sensor.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Furthermore, this novel routing can also guarantee the minimum delivery latency from each source to the sink.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Performance improvements of up to 12-fold and 11-fold are observed in terms of routing traffic load reduction and energy efficiency, respectively, as compared to existing schemes.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Operating systems for wireless sensor network nodes are typically less complex than general-purpose operating systems.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] They more strongly resemble embedded systems, for two reasons.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] First, wireless sensor networks are typically deployed with a particular application in mind, rather than as a general platform.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Second, a need for low costs and low power leads most wireless sensor nodes to have low-power microcontrollers ensuring that mechanisms such as virtual memory are either unnecessary or too expensive to implement.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] It is therefore possible to use embedded operating systems such as eCos or uC/OS for sensor networks.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] However, such operating systems are often designed with real-time properties.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS, developed by David Culler, is perhaps the first operating system specifically designed for wireless sensor networks.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS is based on an event-driven programming model instead of multithreading.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS programs are composed of *event handlers* and *tasks* with run-to-completion semantics.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] When an external event occurs, such as an incoming data packet or a sensor reading, TinyOS signals the appropriate event handler to handle the event.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Event handlers can post tasks that are scheduled by the TinyOS kernel some time later.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] LiteOS is a newly developed OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides UNIX-like abstraction and support for the C programming language.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Contiki, developed by Adam Dunkels, is an OS which uses a simpler programming style in C while providing advances such as 6LoWPAN and Protothreads.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] RIOT (operating system) is a more recent real-time OS including similar functionality to Contiki.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] PreonVM is an OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides 6LoWPAN based on Contiki and support for the Java programming language.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Examples include Xively and the Wikisensing platform Archived 2021-06-09 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Such platforms simplify online collaboration between users over diverse data sets ranging from energy and environment data to that collected from transport services.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Other services include allowing developers to embed real-time graphs & widgets in websites; analyse and process historical data pulled from the data feeds; send real-time alerts from any datastream to control scripts, devices and environments.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] At present, agent-based modeling and simulation is the only paradigm which allows the simulation of complex behavior in the environments of wireless sensors (such as flocking).
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based simulation of wireless sensor and ad hoc networks is a relatively new paradigm.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based modelling was originally based on social simulation.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Network simulators like Opnet, Tetcos NetSim and NS can be used to simulate a wireless sensor network.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Network localization refers to the problem of estimating the location of wireless sensor nodes during deployments and in dynamic settings.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] For ultra-low power sensors, size, cost and environment precludes the use of Global Positioning System receivers on sensors.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] In 2000, Nirupama Bulusu, John Heidemann and Deborah Estrin first motivated and proposed a radio connectivity based system for localization of wireless sensor networks.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Subsequently, such localization systems have been referred to as range free localization systems, and many localization systems for wireless sensor networks have been subsequently proposed including AHLoS, APS, and Stardust.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Sensors and devices used in wireless sensor networks are state-of-the-art technology with the lowest possible price.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The sensor measurements we get from these devices are therefore often noisy, incomplete and inaccurate.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers studying wireless sensor networks hypothesize that much more information can be extracted from hundreds of unreliable measurements spread across a field of interest than from a smaller number of high-quality, high-reliability instruments with the same total cost.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Macro-programming is a term coined by Matt Welsh.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] It refers to programming the entire sensor network as an ensemble, rather than individual sensor nodes.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Another way to macro-program a network is to view the sensor network as a database, which was popularized by the TinyDB system developed by Sam Madden.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Reprogramming is the process of updating the code on the sensor nodes.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The most feasible form of reprogramming is remote reprogramming whereby the code is disseminated wirelessly while the nodes are deployed.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Different reprogramming protocols exist that provide different levels of speed of operation, reliability, energy expenditure, requirement of code resident on the nodes, suitability to different wireless environments, resistance to DoS, etc.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Infrastructure-less architecture (i.e. no gateways are included, etc.) and inherent requirements (i.e. unattended working environment, etc.) of WSNs might pose several weak points that attract adversaries.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, security is a big concern when WSNs are deployed for special applications such as military and healthcare.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Owing to their unique characteristics, traditional security methods of computer networks would be useless (or less effective) for WSNs.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Hence, lack of security mechanisms would cause intrusions towards those networks.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] These intrusions need to be detected and mitigation methods should be applied.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] There have been important innovations in securing wireless sensor networks.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Most wireless embedded networks use omni-directional antennas and therefore neighbors can overhear communication in and out of nodes.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] This was used this to develop a primitive called "*local monitoring*" which was used for detection of sophisticated attacks, like blackhole or wormhole, which degrade the throughput of large networks to close-to-zero.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] This primitive has since been used by many researchers and commercial wireless packet sniffers.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] This was subsequently refined for more sophisticated attacks such as with collusion, mobility, and multi-antenna, multi-channel devices.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] If a centralized architecture is used in a sensor network and the central node fails, then the entire network will collapse, however the reliability of the sensor network can be increased by using a distributed control architecture.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] To provide nodes with backup in case of failure of the central node.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] There is also no centralised body to allocate the resources and they have to be self organized.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] The data gathered from wireless sensor networks is usually saved in the form of numerical data in a central base station.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] To reduce communication costs some algorithms remove or reduce nodes' redundant sensor information and avoid forwarding data that is of no use.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] This technique has been used, for instance, for distributed anomaly detection or distributed optimization.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] As nodes can inspect the data they forward, they can measure averages or directionality for example of readings from other nodes.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] For example, in sensing and monitoring applications, it is generally the case that neighboring sensor nodes monitoring an environmental feature typically register similar values.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] This kind of data redundancy due to the spatial correlation between sensor observations inspires techniques for in-network data aggregation and mining.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation reduces the amount of network traffic which helps to reduce energy consumption on sensor nodes.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] This is a form of in-network processing where sensor nodes are assumed to be unsecured with limited available energy, while the base station is assumed to be secure with unlimited available energy.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation complicates the already existing security challenges for wireless sensor networks and requires new security techniques tailored specifically for these scenarios.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Providing security to aggregate data in wireless sensor networks is known as *secure data aggregation in WSN*. were the first few works discussing techniques for secure data aggregation in wireless sensor networks.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Two main security challenges in secure data aggregation are confidentiality and integrity of data.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] While encryption is traditionally used to provide end to end confidentiality in wireless sensor network, the aggregators in a secure data aggregation scenario need to decrypt the encrypted data to perform aggregation.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] This exposes the plaintext at the aggregators, making the data vulnerable to attacks from an adversary.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Similarly an aggregator can inject false data into the aggregate and make the base station accept false data.
[src:zigbee-3/wireless-sensor-network] Thus, while data aggregation improves energy efficiency of a network, it complicates the existing security challenges.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The technology defined by the Zigbee specification is intended to be simpler and less expensive than other wireless personal area networks (WPANs), such as Bluetooth, or more general wireless networking standards, such as Wi-Fi (or Li-Fi).
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Applications include wireless light switches, home energy monitors, traffic management systems, and other consumer and industrial equipment that requires short-range, low-rate wireless data transfer.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Its low power consumption limits transmission distances to 10–100 meters (33–328 ft) line-of-sight, depending on power output and environmental characteristics.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee devices can transmit data over long distances by passing data through a mesh network of intermediate devices to reach more distant ones.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee is typically used in low-data-rate applications that require long battery life and secure networking.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] (Zigbee networks are secured by 128-bit symmetric encryption keys.) Zigbee has a defined rate of up to 250 kbit/s, best suited for intermittent data transmissions from a sensor or input device.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee was conceived in 1998, standardized in 2003, and revised in 2006.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The name refers to the waggle dance of honey bees after their return to the beehive.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee is a low-power wireless mesh network standard delivering low-latency communication and targeted at battery-powered devices in wireless control and monitoring applications.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee chips are typically integrated with radios and microcontrollers.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee operates in the industrial, scientific and medical (ISM) radio bands, with the 2.4 GHz band being primarily used for lighting and home automation devices in most jurisdictions worldwide.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Devices for commercial utility metering and medical device data collection often use *sub-GHz* frequencies: 902–928 MHz in North America, Australia, and Israel, 868–870 MHz in Europe, 779–787 MHz in China.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Data rates vary from around 20 kbit/s for sub-GHz bands to around 250 kbit/s for the 2.4 GHz band.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee builds on the physical layer and media access control defined in the IEEE 802.15.4 standard for low-rate wireless personal area networks (WPANs).
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The Zigbee specification includes four additional key components: network layer, application layer, *Zigbee Device Objects* (ZDOs) and manufacturer-defined application objects.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] ZDOs are responsible for tasks including keeping track of device roles, managing requests to join a network, and discovering and securing devices.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The Zigbee network layer natively supports star and tree, and generic mesh networking topologies.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Every network must have one coordinator device.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Within star networks, the coordinator must be the central node.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Both trees and meshes allow the use of Zigbee routers to extend communication at the network layer.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Another defining feature of Zigbee is facilities for carrying out secure communications, protecting the establishment and transport of cryptographic keys, ciphering frames, and controlling devices.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] For this, it builds on the basic security framework defined in IEEE 802.15.4.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee-style self-organizing ad hoc digital radio networks were conceived in the 1990s.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The IEEE 802.15.4-2003 Zigbee specification was ratified on December 14, 2004.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The Connectivity Standards Alliance (formerly Zigbee Alliance) announced availability of Specification 1.0 on June 13, 2005, known as the *ZigBee 2004 Specification*.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] In September 2006, the *Zigbee 2006 Specification* was announced, obsoleting the 2004 stack The 2006 specification replaces the message and key–value pair structure used in the 2004 stack with a *cluster library*.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The library is a set of standardised commands, attributes and global artifacts organised under groups known as clusters with names such as Smart Energy, Home Automation, and **Zigbee Light Link**.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Since its unveiling, Dotdot has functioned as the default application layer for almost all Zigbee devices.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee Pro, also known as Zigbee 2007, was finalized in 2007.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] A Zigbee Pro device may join and operate on a legacy Zigbee network and vice versa.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Due to differences in routing options, a Zigbee Pro device must become a non-routing Zigbee End Device (ZED) on a legacy Zigbee network, and a legacy Zigbee device must become a ZED on a Zigbee Pro network.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] It operates using the 2.4 GHz ISM band and adds a sub-GHz band.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee protocols are intended for embedded applications requiring low power consumption and tolerating low data rates.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The resulting network will use very little power—individual devices must have a battery life of at least two years to pass certification.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee is not for situations with high mobility among nodes.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Hence, it is not suitable for tactical ad hoc radio networks in the battlefield, where high data rate and high mobility is present and needed.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The first Zigbee application profile, Home Automation, was announced November 2, 2007.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Additional application profiles have since been published.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The **Zigbee Smart Energy 2.0** specifications define an Internet Protocol-based communication protocol to monitor, control, inform, and automate the delivery and use of energy and water.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] It is an enhancement of the Zigbee Smart Energy version 1 specifications.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] It adds services for plug-in electric vehicle charging, installation, configuration and firmware download, prepay services, user information and messaging, load control, demand response and common information and application profile interfaces for wired and wireless networks.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee Smart Energy relies on Zigbee IP, a network layer that routes standard IPv6 traffic over IEEE 802.15.4 using 6LoWPAN header compression.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] In 2009, the Radio Frequency for Consumer Electronics Consortium (RF4CE) and Connectivity Standards Alliance (formerly Zigbee Alliance) agreed to jointly deliver a standard for radio frequency remote controls.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee RF4CE is designed for a broad range of consumer electronics products, such as TVs and set-top boxes.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] It promised many advantages over existing remote control solutions, including richer communication and increased reliability, enhanced features and flexibility, interoperability, and no line-of-sight barrier.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The Zigbee RF4CE specification uses a subset of Zigbee functionality allowing to run on smaller memory configurations in lower-cost devices, such as remote control of consumer electronics.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The radio design used by Zigbee has few analog stages and uses digital circuits wherever possible.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Products that integrate the radio and microcontroller into a single module are available.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The Zigbee qualification process involves a full validation of the requirements of the physical layer.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] All radios derived from the same validated semiconductor mask set would enjoy the same RF characteristics.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee radios have very tight constraints on power and bandwidth.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] An uncertified physical layer that malfunctions can increase the power consumption of other devices on a Zigbee network.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Thus, radios are tested with guidance given by Clause 6 of the 802.15.4-2006 Standard.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] This standard specifies operation in the unlicensed 2.4 to 2.4835 GHz (worldwide), 902 to 928 MHz (Americas and Australia) and 868 to 868.6 MHz (Europe) ISM bands.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Sixteen channels are allocated in the 2.4 GHz band, spaced 5 MHz apart, though using only 2 MHz of bandwidth each.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The radios use direct-sequence spread spectrum coding, which is managed by the digital stream into the modulator.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Binary phase-shift keying (BPSK) is used in the 868 and 915 MHz bands, and offset quadrature phase-shift keying (OQPSK) that transmits two bits per symbol is used in the 2.4 GHz band.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The raw, over-the-air data rate is 250 kbit/s per channel in the 2.4 GHz band, 40 kbit/s per channel in the 915 MHz band, and 20 kbit/s in the 868 MHz band.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The actual data throughput will be less than the maximum specified bit rate because of the packet overhead and processing delays.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] For indoor applications at 2.4 GHz, the transmission distance is 10–20 m, depending on the construction materials, the number of walls to be penetrated and the output power permitted in the geographical location.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The output power of the radios is generally 0–20 dBm (1–100 mW).
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The current Zigbee protocols support beacon-enabled and non-beacon-enabled networks.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] In non-beacon-enabled networks, an unslotted CSMA/CA channel access mechanism is used.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] In this type of network, Zigbee routers typically have their receivers continuously active, requiring additional power.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] However, this allows for heterogeneous networks in which some devices receive continuously while others transmit when necessary.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The typical example of a heterogeneous network is a wireless light switch: The Zigbee node at the lamp may constantly receive, since it is reliably powered by the mains supply to the lamp, while a battery-powered light switch would remain asleep until the switch is thrown.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] In this case, the switch wakes up, sends a command to the lamp, receives an acknowledgment, and returns to sleep.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] In such a network, the lamp node will be at least a Zigbee router, if not the Zigbee coordinator; the switch node is typically a Zigbee end device.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] In beacon-enabled networks, Zigbee routers transmit periodic beacons to confirm their presence to other network nodes.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Nodes may sleep between beacons, thus extending their battery life.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Beacon intervals depend on data rate; they may range from 15.36 milliseconds to 251.65824 seconds at 250 kbit/s, from 24 milliseconds to 393.216 seconds at 40 kbit/s and from 48 milliseconds to 786.432 seconds at 20 kbit/s.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Long beacon intervals require precise timing, which can be expensive to implement in low-cost products.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] In general, the Zigbee protocols minimize the time the radio is on, so as to reduce power use.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] In beaconing networks, nodes only need to be active while a beacon is being transmitted.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] In non-beacon-enabled networks, power consumption is decidedly asymmetrical: Some devices are always active while others spend most of their time sleeping.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Except for Smart Energy Profile 2.0, Zigbee devices are required to conform to the IEEE 802.15.4-2003 Low-rate Wireless Personal Area Network (LR-WPAN) standard.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The standard specifies the lower protocol layers—the physical layer (PHY), and the media access control portion of the data link layer.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The basic channel access mode is carrier-sense multiple access with collision avoidance (CSMA/CA).
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] That is, the nodes communicate in a way somewhat analogous to how humans converse: a node briefly checks to see that other nodes are not talking before it starts.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The main functions of the network layer are to ensure correct use of the MAC sublayer and provide a suitable interface for use by the next upper layer, namely the application layer.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The network layer deals with network functions such as connecting, disconnecting, and setting up networks.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] It can establish a network, allocate addresses, and add and remove devices.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] This layer makes use of star, mesh and tree topologies.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The data entity of the transport layer creates and manages protocol data units at the direction of the application layer and performs routing according to the current topology.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The control entity handles the configuration of new devices and establishes new networks.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] It can determine whether a neighboring device belongs to the network and discover new neighbors and routers.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The routing protocol used by the network layer is AODV.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] To find a destination device, AODV is used to broadcast a route request to all of its neighbors.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The neighbors then broadcast the request to their neighbors and onward until the destination is reached.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Once the destination is reached, a route reply is sent via unicast transmission following the lowest cost path back to the source.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Once the source receives the reply, it updates its routing table with the destination address of the next hop in the path and the associated path cost.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The application layer is the highest-level layer defined by the specification and is the effective interface of the Zigbee system to its end users.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] It comprises the majority of components added by the Zigbee specification: both ZDO (Zigbee device object) and its management procedures, together with application objects defined by the manufacturer, are considered part of this layer.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] This layer binds tables, sends messages between bound devices, manages group addresses, reassembles packets, and transports data.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] It is responsible for providing service to Zigbee device profiles.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The *ZDO* (Zigbee device object), a protocol in the Zigbee protocol stack, is responsible for overall device management, security keys, and policies.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] It is responsible for defining the role of a device as either coordinator or end device, as mentioned above, but also for the discovery of new devices on the network and the identification of their offered services.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] It may then go on to establish secure links with external devices and reply to binding requests accordingly.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The application support sublayer (APS) is the other main standard component of the stack, and as such, it offers a well-defined interface and control services.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] It works as a bridge between the network layer and the other elements of the application layer: it keeps up-to-date binding tables in the form of a database, which can be used to find appropriate devices depending on the services that are needed and those that the different devices offer.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] As the union between both specified layers, it also routes messages across the layers of the protocol stack.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] An application may consist of communicating objects that cooperate to carry out the desired tasks.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Tasks will typically be largely local to each device, such as the control of each household appliance.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The focus of Zigbee is to distribute work among many different devices that reside within individual Zigbee nodes, which in turn form a network.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The objects that form the network communicate using the facilities provided by APS, supervised by ZDO interfaces.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Within a single device, up to 240 application objects can exist, numbered in the range 1–240.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] 0 is reserved for the ZDO data interface and 255 for broadcast; the 241–254 range is not in use but may be in the future.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Addressing is also part of the application layer.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] A network node consists of an IEEE 802.15.4-conformant radio transceiver and one or more device descriptions (collections of attributes that can be polled or set or can be monitored through events).
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The transceiver is the basis for addressing, and devices within a node are specified by an *endpoint identifier* in the range 1 to 240.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] For applications to communicate, the devices that support them must use a common application protocol (types of messages, formats and so on); these sets of conventions are grouped in *profiles*.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Furthermore, binding is decided upon by matching input and output cluster identifiers unique within the context of a given profile and associated with an incoming or outgoing data flow in a device.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Binding tables contain source and destination pairs.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Depending on the available information, device discovery may follow different methods.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] When the network address is known, the IEEE address can be requested using unicast communication.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] When it is not, petitions are broadcast.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] End devices will simply respond with the requested address, while a network coordinator or a router will also send the addresses of all the devices associated with it.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] This extended discovery protocol permits external devices to find out about devices in a network and the services that they offer, which endpoints can report when queried by the discovering device (which has previously obtained their addresses).
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The use of cluster identifiers enforces the binding of complementary entities using the binding tables, which are maintained by Zigbee coordinators, as the table must always be available within a network and coordinators are most likely to have a permanent power supply.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Backups, managed by higher-level layers, may be needed by some applications.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Binding requires an established communication link; after it exists, whether to add a new node to the network is decided, according to the application and security policies.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Communication can happen right after the association.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] *Direct addressing* uses both radio address and endpoint identifier, whereas indirect addressing uses every relevant field (address, endpoint, cluster, and attribute) and requires that they are sent to the network coordinator, which maintains associations and translates requests for communication.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Indirect addressing is particularly useful to keep some devices very simple and minimize their need for storage.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Besides these two methods, *broadcast* to all endpoints in a device is available, and *group addressing* is used to communicate with groups of endpoints belonging to a specified set of devices.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] As one of its defining features, Zigbee provides facilities for carrying out secure communications, protecting the establishment and transport of cryptographic keys and encrypting data.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] It builds on the basic security framework defined in IEEE 802.15.4.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The basic mechanism to ensure confidentiality is the adequate protection of all keying material.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Keys are the cornerstone of the security architecture; as such, their protection is of paramount importance, and keys are never supposed to be transported through an insecure channel.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] A momentary exception to this rule occurs during the initial phase of the addition to the network of a previously unconfigured device.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Trust must be assumed in the initial installation of the keys, as well as in the processing of security information.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The Zigbee network model must take particular care of security considerations, as ad hoc networks may be physically accessible to external devices.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Also, the state of the working environment cannot be predicted.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Within the protocol stack, different network layers are not cryptographically separated, so access policies are needed, and conventional design assumed.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The open trust model within a device allows for key sharing, which notably decreases potential cost.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Nevertheless, the layer that creates a frame is responsible for its security.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] As malicious devices may exist, every network layer payload must be ciphered, so unauthorized traffic can be immediately cut off.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The exception, again, is the transmission of the network key, which confers a unified security layer to the grid to a new connecting device.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The Zigbee security architecture is based on CCM*, which adds encryption- and integrity-only features to CCM mode.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Zigbee uses 128-bit keys to implement its security mechanisms.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] A key can be associated either with a network, being usable by Zigbee layers and the MAC sublayer, or to a link, acquired through pre-installation, agreement or transport.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Establishment of link keys is based on a master key that controls link key correspondence.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Ultimately, at least, the initial master key must be obtained through a secure medium (transport or pre-installation), as the security of the whole network depends on it.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Link and master keys are only visible to the application layer.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Different services use different one-way variations of the link key to avoid leaks and security risks.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Key distribution is one of the most important security functions of the network.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] A secure network will designate one special device, the *trust center*, which other devices trust for the distribution of security keys.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Ideally, devices will have the trust center address and initial master key preloaded; if a momentary vulnerability is allowed, it will be sent as described above.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Typical applications without special security needs will use a network key provided by the trust center (through the initially insecure channel) to communicate.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Thus, the trust center maintains both the network key and provides point-to-point security.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Devices will only accept communications originating from a key supplied by the trust center, except for the initial master key.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] According to the German computer e-magazine *Heise Online*, Zigbee Home Automation 1.2 uses fallback keys for encryption negotiation, which are known and can not be changed.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] This makes the encryption highly vulnerable.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] This ensures that all network traffic is securely encrypted even while pairing the device.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] In addition, all Zigbee devices need to randomize their network key, no matter which pairing method they use, thereby improving security for older devices.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] The Zigbee coordinator within the Zigbee network can be set to deny access to devices that do not employ this key randomization, further increasing security.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] In addition, the Zigbee 3.0 protocol features countermeasures against removing already paired devices from the network with the intention of listening to the key exchange when re-pairing.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] Network simulators, like ns-2, OMNeT++, OPNET, and NetSim can be used to simulate IEEE 802.15.4 Zigbee networks.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] These simulators come with open source C or C++ libraries for users to modify.
[src:zigbee-3/zigbee] This way, users can determine the validity of new algorithms before hardware implementation.
